04300nam a22006015i 9780292796201DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927962017 a10.7560/7069722doi  a(DE-B1597)587691  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPQ7207.M48P37 2005 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a868/.608093582221 aParra, Max, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWriting Pancho Villa's Revolution :bRebels in the Literary Imagination of Mexico /cMax Parra. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (197 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 The politics of incorporation: the Calles era, 1925 –1935 -- tChapter 2 Villa and popular political subjectivity in Mariano Azuela’s Los de Abajo -- tChapter 3 Reconstructing subaltern perspectives in Nellie Campobello’s Cartucho -- tChapter 4 Villismo and intellectual authority in Martín Luis Guzmán’s El águila y la serpiente -- tChapter 5 Soldierly honor and mexicanness in Rafael F. Muñoz’s ¡Vámonos con Pancho Villa! -- tChapter 6 The battle for Pancho villa during Cardenismo, 1935 –1940 -- tChapter 7 Villismo’s legacy -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1910 Mexican Revolution saw Francisco "Pancho" Villa grow from social bandit to famed revolutionary leader. Although his rise to national prominence was short-lived, he and his followers (the villistas) inspired deep feelings of pride and power amongst the rural poor. After the Revolution (and Villa's ultimate defeat and death), the new ruling elite, resentful of his enormous popularity, marginalized and discounted him and his followers as uncivilized savages. Hence, it was in the realm of culture rather than politics that his true legacy would be debated and shaped. Mexican literature following the Revolution created an enduring image of Villa and his followers. Writing Pancho Villa's Revolution focuses on the novels, chronicles, and testimonials written from 1925 to 1940 that narrated Villa's grassroots insurgency and celebrated—or condemned—his charismatic leadership. By focusing on works by urban writers Mariano Azuela (Los de abajo) and Martín Luis Guzmán (El águila y la serpiente), as well as works closer to the violent tradition of northern Mexican frontier life by Nellie Campobello (Cartucho), Celia Herrera (Villa ante la historia), and Rafael F. Muñoz (¡Vámonos con Pancho Villa!), this book examines the alternative views of the revolution and of the villistas. Max Parra studies how these works articulate different and at times competing views about class and the cultural "otherness" of the rebellious masses. This unique revisionist study of the villista novel also offers a deeper look into the process of how a nation's collective identity is formed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMexican prose literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796201423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796201/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK